    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's get back to the technical explanation.\n\nIn terms of acoustics and frequency ratios, a minor second is considered dissonant because it corresponds to a frequency ratio of 9:8, which is not a simple harmonic ratio. This ratio is not a whole number multiple of the fundamental frequency, which is why it creates a sense of tension.\n\nOn the other hand, a perfect fifth is a frequency ratio of 3:2, which is a simple harmonic ratio that corresponds to the harmonic series. This ratio is a whole number multiple of the fundamental frequency, which is why it creates a sense of resolution.\n\nTo illustrate this, imagine two strings of different lengths, plucked at the same time. The string with the longer length will produce a lower frequency, while the shorter string will produce a higher frequency. When these two frequencies are combined, they create an interference pattern that can be analyzed using Fourier analysis.\n\nThe frequency ratio of 9:8 in a minor second corresponds to a specific interference pattern, which is not as coherent as the 3:2 ratio of a perfect fifth. This incoherence is what makes the minor second sound dissonant to our ears.",
      "source": "target",
