      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The dissonance caused by the minor second is indeed related to the physical interference of the waves, specifically the beat frequencies. When two frequencies are close together, like the 9:8 ratio of a minor second, they produce a beat frequency that is the difference between the two frequencies.\n\nIn the ear, the beat frequency is perceived as a pulsating or wavering sensation, often described as a \"vibrato\" or \"tremolo\". This is because the ear is sensitive to the difference in amplitude between the two frequencies, rather than the absolute frequencies themselves.\n\nThink of it like a goblin trying to sneak up on a sleeping goblin - the beat frequency is like the goblin's footsteps, which create a subtle vibration that the sleeping goblin (our ear) can detect. This vibration is what we perceive as dissonance or tension.\n\nWhen the beat frequency is strong enough, it can create a sense of discomfort or unease, which is why minor seconds are often used in music to create a sense of drama or tension. On the other hand, when the beat frequency is weak, it can create a sense of resolution or consonance, which is why perfect fifths are often used to create a sense of closure.",
